 a novel first published in 1719)."],"variants":[{"name":"Robbinson","meanings":["Altered form of English or French   Robinson  ."]},{"name":"Robin","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Pierre, Andre, Emile, Marcel, Achille, Armand, Arnaud, Camille, Julien, Michel, Normand.","French, Breton, Scottish, English, and German: from the personal name <i>Robin</i>, a pet form of   Robert  , composed of the short form <i>Rob</i> + the hypocoristic suffix <i>-in</i>.","Slovenian: topographic name derived from <i>rob</i> ‘edge, border’ (see   Robar  )."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Alice Robinson was born about 1520. She married William Banks about 1550. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 3 daughters."},"et":{"Abt 1520–":"umbes 1520–Surnud","1530–1577":"1530–1577","1555–1626":"1555–1626","1558–1613":"1558–1613","1560–1660":"1560–1660","1560–Female":"1560–Surnud","1561–Female":"1561–Surnud","1520–Female":"1520–Surnud","1561":"1561","1660":"1660","1560":"1560","Abt 1555":"umbes 1555","Abt 1558":"umbes 1558","Abt 1560":"umbes 1560","1613":"1613","1558":"1558","1555":"1555","1577":"1577","Abt 1520":"umbes 1520","1520":"1520","153